SIMPLE: overshadow
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Overshadow
<hw>O`ver*shad"ow</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Overshadowed</conjf><pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Overshadowing</conjf>. ]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf.
<er>Overshade</er>. ]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To throw a shadow, or
shade, over; to darken; to obscure.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There was a cloud that <qex>overshadowed</qex> them.</q>
<rj><qau>Mark ix. 7.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>Fig.:</specif> <def>To cover with a superior
influence; to be viewed as more important than.</def>
<rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To cause to be sad or disappointing; to cast a sad
shadow on; <as>as, an accidental death <ex>overshadowed</ex> the joy of
the festival</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Overshadower</ent>⟦br⟧
